properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls may develop this evening and possibly persist through Saturday. Locally heavy snow squalls are expected to develop this evening as strong southwesterly winds develop off of Lake Ontario. These snow squalls could possibly last until Saturday afternoon. Snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm are possible by Saturday afternoon. Given the strong winds gusting 60 to 80 km/h, areas of near zero visibilities in blowing snow and heavy falling snow could make travel hazardous across the region. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls may develop this afternoon and possibly persist through Saturday morning. Locally heavy snow squalls are expected to develop this afternoon as strong southwesterly winds develop off of Lake Erie. These snow squalls could possibly last until Saturday morning. These snow squall bands could shift across the region which could limit the snowfall amount over a given location. Local snowfall amounts near 15 cm are possible with these snow squalls. However, if the strongest snow squall from Lake Erie is able to lock in and become stationary for a few hours, snowfall amounts of up to 25 cm are possible. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An arctic ridge of high pressure will allow for a very cold air mass from the north to sink over portions of southern and central Saskatchewan today. Along with winds of 10 to 20 km/h, extreme wind chill values of -40 or colder are expected occur this morning. Many areas rebound only slightly from these bitterly cold values during the day before another round of more expansive cold sets in across the province Friday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. A ridge of arctic high pressure will keep skies relatively clear and allow for a very cold air mass to move into portions of northern Manitoba from Nunavut. Along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h, extreme cold wind chills of -45 or colder are expected over the next few days as the stagnant area of high pressure remains parked over the province. Extreme cold warnings will likely be expanded to include most of the province come Friday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Sant at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
